{"type":"failure","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-10T03:13:50.439Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-f3bb","commit":"51fe4bc3e573ee77e8c75b6e68d7abd8e526fb35"},"description":"claude-code agent terminates with stop_reason=end_turn while a long-running command (bun install, Monitor poll, background bash) is still in flight. The model emits a natural-language assistant message like 'I'll wait for the install to finish' with no tool call; claude-code's run loop reads that as turn-complete and returns to the operator. In warren there is no operator to send the next prompt, so the run reaps before commit/push/finalize ever runs. Witnessed in run_a98cfx1fantf seq:105-106, compounded with warren-f3bb's silent-empty-branch path. Symptom: result subtype=success is_error=false but workspace branch has zero new commits because the agent self-described as mid-task.","resolution":"Updated canopy claude-code prompt (canopy-daf3) v4 with explicit Expectations bullet: 'Never end your turn with work in flight. ... Polling output is not the same as done.' Cheap, narrow, fixes the witnessed instance. For other runtimes hitting variants of this seam, file a separate seed before generalizing — warren-side detection (B) and burrow-side wait-on-subprocess (C) are speculative and were deferred.","id":"mx-2fea6d"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-06-06T20:00:41.604Z","evidence":{"commit":"850def05c9fb6be33a162c8722de76bb51e92a14"},"content":"TokenConsumptionChart (warren-4dc9) should follow the same data-passing pattern as all other charts on RunAnalytics.tsx: pass 'data?.tokens.xxx ?? []' directly rather than wrapping in '{data ? <Component data={data.tokens.xxx} /> : null}'. The null-conditional + fallback pattern renders the chart in its empty state during loading, consistent with RunsOverTimeChart, FailureReasonChart, etc. (warren-af75 polish).","id":"mx-b3a884"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-08T20:01:11.817Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-4379","commit":"ed69140e0bdcc1fff4f276409e6b941d2abfd27c"},"content":"src/index.ts must contain a top-level `const VERSION = \"x.y.z\";` literal — the publish workflow (.github/workflows/publish.yml) grep-extracts this line and aborts publish if it disagrees with package.json. Do not refactor VERSION into a function call, computed expression, or different file without updating the workflow regex (`grep -oP 'const VERSION = \"\\K[^\"]+' src/index.ts`).","id":"mx-70e9e9"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-08T20:01:14.347Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-4379","commit":"ed69140e0bdcc1fff4f276409e6b941d2abfd27c"},"content":"Package name is `@os-eco/warren-cli` (not `@os-eco/warren` as suggested in SPEC §1, which marks it TBD). The publish workflow npm-views `@os-eco/warren-cli` to gate publishing — keep this name in package.json or the workflow short-circuits. Sibling tools follow the same `*-cli` pattern (`@os-eco/seeds-cli`, `@os-eco/burrow-cli`).","id":"mx-be6bc5"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-08T20:01:18.542Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-4379","commit":"ed69140e0bdcc1fff4f276409e6b941d2abfd27c"},"content":"src/ subdirectory tree (core, registry, projects, runs, burrow-client, supervisor, server, db, cli, ui) is laid out by SPEC §7 but materialised lazily — each phase (warren-35db onward) creates the files it needs. Phase 0 only ships src/index.ts (VERSION) + src/cli/main.ts (commander wiring) + src/index.test.ts (smoke test). Do not pre-stub empty modules; let later phases own their files.","id":"mx-d5fe85"}
{"type":"pattern","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-08T20:01:24.220Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-4379","commit":"ed69140e0bdcc1fff4f276409e6b941d2abfd27c"},"name":"Quality gates triplet","description":"Quality gates are `bun test && bun run lint && bun run typecheck` (the same triplet CONTRIBUTING.md and .github/workflows/ci.yml require). Biome config is tab indent + 100-col, with `noUnusedVariables/Imports/FunctionParameters` and `noExplicitAny` as errors — same posture as @os-eco/seeds. Run all three before committing; CI will reject on any failure.","files":[".gitignore",".seeds/issues.jsonl",".seeds/plans.jsonl","SPEC.md"],"id":"mx-b20bcc"}
{"type":"reference","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-08T20:01:28.690Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-4379","commit":"ed69140e0bdcc1fff4f276409e6b941d2abfd27c"},"name":"Sibling repo configs","description":"When scaffolding new pieces (db config, server skeleton, CLI command shape), reference `/Users/jayminwest/Projects/os-eco/burrow` and `/Users/jayminwest/Projects/os-eco/seeds` first — they pin the os-eco-wide conventions warren follows: tsconfig (strict + noUncheckedIndexedAccess + allowImportingTsExtensions), biome (tab + 100-col), commander CLI shape, drizzle.config.ts pattern. Burrow is the closest in domain (HTTP server + drizzle + supervisor) and the most useful template.","files":[".gitignore",".seeds/issues.jsonl",".seeds/plans.jsonl","SPEC.md"],"id":"mx-27f236"}
{"type":"decision","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-08T20:19:03.418Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-345f","commit":"0754dccf3b6d70961f28310434b637059cfacb8c"},"title":"Wire @os-eco/burrow-cli via file:../burrow until burrow is published","rationale":"Burrow's HttpClient (lib/http-client.ts) is warren's only seam to the runtime, but @os-eco/burrow-cli isn't on npm yet. file:../burrow makes the sibling repo install resolvable in this monorepo layout (bun install creates a symlink-ish copy under node_modules/@os-eco/burrow-cli). Flip to a semver range when burrow ships — warren-345f tracks. Don't inline-copy burrow's wire types; they need to stay in lockstep with burrow's server responses.","id":"mx-4925ca"}
{"type":"failure","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-08T20:19:25.947Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-c0e6","commit":"0754dccf3b6d70961f28310434b637059cfacb8c"},"description":"TypeScript test stubs for typeof fetch fail strict typecheck because fetch's signature requires a preconnect() method that bare async functions lack (Property 'preconnect' is missing in type ...). Resolution: cast via a small helper, e.g. function stub(impl): typeof fetch { return impl as unknown as typeof fetch; }. Don't try to satisfy the full Function-with-preconnect shape — preconnect is never invoked by fetch consumers in tests.","resolution":"Use a stub() helper in test files that does 'return impl as unknown as typeof fetch'. Lint allows it; tsc passes; runtime is unaffected because consumer code never calls fetch.preconnect.","id":"mx-8aaa30"}
{"type":"failure","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-08T20:36:56.866Z","evidence":{"commit":"b7a56a783f0b3fcdc8a91a2641e39ee83c84b8ac"},"description":"Bun's biome formatter rewrites multi-line throw-with-options-object into a single line up to lineWidth=100, but only after the lint rule fires. Long error messages with template literals + recoveryHint object commonly fail format check on first write.","resolution":"Run 'bun run lint:fix' before committing. The auto-fix is mechanical and safe; the rewrite is purely cosmetic.","id":"mx-1ec3f5"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-08T21:58:29.420Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-b057","commit":"cc6aad2d62833aab46bb2d425a6ec6065cd3f7cd"},"content":"UI build entrypoint from repo root: 'bun run build:ui' shells 'cd src/ui && bun install && bun run build'. Output lands at src/ui/dist/{index.html, assets/*}. Server picks it up via WARREN_UI_DIST_DIR (defaults to <cwd>/src/ui/dist via src/server/config.ts:resolveUiDistDir). UI handler (src/server/ui.ts) refuses /agents, /projects, /runs, /healthz, /readyz prefixes and falls through to index.html for any other GET so the SPA can render deep links.","id":"mx-3c5052"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-08T22:30:45.230Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-2646","commit":"7427661b741e8a99989433424e20209eb32d9b6a"},"content":"Container ENTRYPOINT is 'bun run src/supervisor/main.ts', NOT warren or burrow directly. The supervisor (src/supervisor/main.ts) owns boot ordering (spawn burrow, wait for socket, then spawn warren), signal forwarding (SIGTERM/SIGINT to both children with 5s grace), and burrow restart policy (5-in-60s budget). Both Dockerfile and fly.toml reference the supervisor as the entrypoint.","id":"mx-0be64b"}
{"type":"decision","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-08T22:30:53.462Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-2646","commit":"7427661b741e8a99989433424e20209eb32d9b6a"},"title":"Two-stage Dockerfile: ui-builder + runtime-from-burrow-base","rationale":"Stage 1 (oven/bun:1.1 AS ui-builder) builds the React/Vite SPA and emits dist/. Stage 2 extends ghcr.io/jayminwest/burrow-base:0.2.0 (which provides bun + bwrap + uidmap + burrow CLI), installs the four os-eco CLIs warren shells out to (canopy/seeds/mulch/sapling), copies warren source, then COPYs the prebuilt UI bundle from stage 1. This avoids shipping node_modules for the UI in the final image and avoids running 'bun run build:ui' inside the runtime stage where the Vite toolchain isn't otherwise needed.","id":"mx-689d86"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-08T22:30:57.547Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-2646","commit":"7427661b741e8a99989433424e20209eb32d9b6a"},"content":"docker-compose.yml applies the four bwrap-friendly security flags (apparmor=unconfined, seccomp=unconfined, systempaths=unconfined, cap_add: SYS_ADMIN) to the warren service. fly.toml does NOT set these — Fly Machines are Firecracker VMs, not containers, and bwrap nests on a stock Machine kernel. Same image, different container posture per orchestrator. See burrow/DEPLOY.md for the underlying recipe (mx-94901b/mx-c085ba).","id":"mx-5d61d1"}
{"type":"failure","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-08T22:31:02.575Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-2646","commit":"7427661b741e8a99989433424e20209eb32d9b6a"},"description":"Biome's lint/style/noNonNullAssertion auto-fix (lint:fix) replaces 'arr[idx]!' with 'arr[idx]?', silently turning a compile-time guarantee into a runtime no-op. With noUncheckedIndexedAccess in tsconfig, indexed access is T|undefined; '!' was the assertion the array slot is populated, '?' makes the call (resolveExit, etc.) silently no-op when the slot is empty — masking test bugs.","resolution":"Refactor the test to a for-loop that explicitly throws on undefined: 'for (let i...) { const child = arr[i]; if (child === undefined) throw new Error(...); child.method(); }'. Don't accept the auto-fix.","id":"mx-0469dc"}
{"type":"decision","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-09T17:31:14.575Z","evidence":{"commit":"7df7e86f769425635118042cf68e283e31a05f51"},"relates_to":["mx-be6bc5"],"title":"Warren is not published to npm; container image is the only distribution channel","rationale":"Warren's CLI surface (serve, register-agent, add-project, run, doctor) is server-internal — every command operates on warren's local sqlite and the burrow unix socket inside the deployed container, not on an operator's laptop. Cross-checked the os-eco tree: nothing imports @os-eco/warren-cli or shells out to 'warren'/'wr' (unlike burrow, which overstory/sapling/the warren Dockerfile itself all install globally). The Dockerfile also bakes warren via COPY of source rather than 'bun install -g @os-eco/warren-cli', so even warren's own deploy did not consume itself from npm. The container image (Fly Machine / docker-compose, per SPEC §10.2/10.3) is the canonical artifact. Maintaining the publish flow (NPM_TOKEN secret, version-sync check against src/index.ts, CHANGELOG discipline) was overhead with zero consumers, and a published @os-eco/warren-cli would have invited users to 'npm i -g' it and hit confusing failures running 'wr serve' outside the container.","id":"mx-834a3a"}
{"type":"failure","classification":"foundational","recorded_at":"2026-05-09T17:38:59.426Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-274c","commit":"d3eebec60e5e57612d261cfe832508db1d5ed02f"},"tags":["deploy","bun","docker","supervisor","gotcha"],"description":"When warren's supervisor calls Bun.spawn({ cmd: ['burrow', ...], cwd: '/app' }), Bun resolves 'burrow' via /app/node_modules/.bin/burrow BEFORE walking PATH. So a Dockerfile that 'bun install -g' a newer @os-eco/burrow-cli to /usr/local/bin/burrow has zero effect on the supervisor's spawned process — it runs the lockfile-pinned local copy. Bumping a CLI that warren both depends on (library) AND ships globally requires updating BOTH the Dockerfile pin AND package.json + bun.lock; otherwise the supervisor runs the stale local bin.","resolution":"Bump @os-eco/burrow-cli (and any other dual-purpose CLI) in three places: Dockerfile global install line, package.json deps, and bun.lock (regenerate via 'bun install'). Verify post-rebuild: docker compose exec warren sh -c 'for pid in /proc/[0-9]*; do tr \"\\\\0\" \" \" < \"$pid/cmdline\"; done | grep burrow.serve' — if the path is /app/node_modules/.bin/burrow, the lockfile pin is what's running.","id":"mx-1dc078"}
{"type":"reference","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-09T17:38:59.747Z","evidence":{"commit":"d3eebec60e5e57612d261cfe832508db1d5ed02f"},"tags":["deploy","bun","docker","claude-code","gotcha"],"name":"claude-code-postinstall-not-run-by-bun-install-g","description":"@anthropic-ai/claude-code declares a postinstall script that downloads the platform-native 'claude' binary. Bun's 'bun install -g' skips lifecycle scripts by default for safety, so the bin shim at /usr/local/bin/claude just prints 'Error: claude native binary not installed' and exits 1. Workaround in Dockerfile: after 'bun install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code@<v>', run 'bun run /root/.bun/install/global/node_modules/@anthropic-ai/claude-code/install.cjs' to invoke the postinstall manually. Same pattern likely applies to any npm package that uses postinstall to fetch native binaries.","files":[".mulch/expertise/build.jsonl"],"id":"mx-f16578"}
{"type":"failure","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-09T17:48:16.350Z","evidence":{"commit":"d7a788e2080bcfdccf4997ea1abdb76323c99c99"},"description":"biome's noFallthroughSwitchClause flags a switch case whose body ends in process.exit() — biome only treats break/return/throw/continue as terminators, not Node's never-returning calls. CI lint failed on scripts/acceptance/run.ts where 'case \"-h\": printHelp(); process.exit(0);' fell through to default.","resolution":"Add an explicit 'break;' after process.exit(0) (it's unreachable but satisfies the rule). Same pattern applies to any switch-case body terminating in process.exit / never-returning helpers.","id":"mx-fba932"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-09T18:37:45.958Z","evidence":{"commit":"eb1a7ca2b39095596b0caa9175e2066f25e6827d"},"content":"release workflow (.github/workflows/release.yml) tags + creates GH release on every push to main where package.json version doesn't yet exist as v$VERSION on origin tags. To cut a new release: bump package.json + src/index.ts VERSION (must match — workflow verifies), add a CHANGELOG.md '## [X.Y.Z]' section, push to main. No npm publish (warren ships as container per mx-834a3a). v0.1.0 was tagged manually before the workflow landed.","id":"mx-101882"}
{"type":"failure","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-09T19:42:50.842Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-b8fc","commit":"b6eb0b6fae36696f6b2e4b1b72472f486ec36851"},"dir_anchors":["src/server"],"description":"bun-types' Serve.Options is XOR(HostnamePortServeOptions, UnixServeOptions); idleTimeout is declared only on the TCP variant, so Bun.serve({ unix, fetch, idleTimeout }) fails typecheck with 'Type number is not assignable to type undefined'. Bun's runtime DOES honor idleTimeout on unix sockets — the type is the gap.","resolution":"Cast through unknown when binding: const opts = { unix, fetch, idleTimeout } as unknown as Parameters<typeof Bun.serve>[0]; return Bun.serve(opts);","id":"mx-780674"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-09T20:06:13.632Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-fab1","commit":"2ac4a3ccbc4d5a25432a049701d2806330a87483"},"content":"Dockerfile must symlink /app/src/cli/main.ts → /usr/local/bin/warren AND /usr/local/bin/wr after the COPY . /app step. The five os-eco CLIs are installed via 'bun install -g' but warren itself is not, so its package.json bin entries (warren, wr) only land on PATH via an explicit symlink. main.ts is +x with a '#!/usr/bin/env bun' shebang so the symlink runs as-is. Without it 'docker compose exec warren warren <subcmd>' fails with 'executable file not found in PATH' and operators must fall back to 'bun /app/src/cli/main.ts'.","id":"mx-62145b"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-09T20:14:52.993Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-bd69","commit":"a07026fa57654d35451b31bc9ade5193f6304f2f"},"content":"Runtime image installs curl alongside bubblewrap/uidmap/git/ca-certificates so first-run diagnostics against the burrow unix socket (curl --unix-socket /var/run/burrow.sock http://localhost/healthz) work out of the box — no bun -e fetch() workarounds. ~1MB image cost; debugging time saved is hours. Don't drop curl when slimming the image without first wiring an alternative diagnostic path.","id":"mx-4c4bee"}
{"type":"failure","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-09T21:33:40.476Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-5f19","commit":"77c006655d9b863c408e8f948c66378fce700341"},"description":"drizzle-kit generate (v0.31.10) for SQLite emits CREATE INDEX with the descending expression wrapped in backticks: CREATE INDEX foo ON runs (`project_id`,`\"started_at\" DESC`). SQLite then treats \"started_at\" DESC as a single literal column name and migrate fails at runtime with 'no such column: \"started_at\" DESC'. The original 0000_init.sql (older drizzle-kit) used the correct form (project_id,\"started_at\" DESC) — no backticks around the expression.","resolution":"After 'bunx drizzle-kit generate', hand-edit the new migration .sql to drop the backticks around any indexed expression like `\"col\" DESC` → \"col\" DESC. The bun-sqlite migrator runs migrations on every openDatabase call, so a bad index expression surfaces immediately in any unit test that opens an in-memory db.","id":"mx-451cd7"}
{"type":"failure","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-09T21:40:38.340Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-1eaa","commit":"490e0efd16934a4ac2abf0f16a56036474fd5005"},"description":"Warren's Dockerfile global bun install lands in /root/.bun/install/global by default, but burrow's sandbox SYSTEM_RO_MOUNTS only ro-binds /usr, /etc, /lib, /lib64, /bin, /sbin, /opt — so /usr/local/bin/{sd,ml,cn,sapling,burrow} symlinks dangle inside the sandbox and the agent can't run any os-eco CLI.","resolution":"Set ENV BUN_INSTALL=/usr/local before 'bun install -g'. Bun then stores packages under /usr/local/install/global/node_modules/, which sits under the /usr ro-bind, so symlinks resolve. Update the explicit claude-code postinstall path to match (/usr/local/install/global/node_modules/@anthropic-ai/claude-code/install.cjs).","id":"mx-92dc4a"}
{"type":"decision","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-10T04:24:05.258Z","evidence":{"commit":"fbf4e250671d952d7287da3025bf72481248969d"},"title":"Acceptance harness wraps burrow serve with a custom entry that registers stub-shell + uses no-bwrap spawn","rationale":"Two upstream gaps blocked acceptance scenarios that need a real running agent: (1) burrow serve's AgentRegistry only carries built-ins; declarative [[agents]] in burrow.toml are read for toolchain mounts but never registered into the runtime registry (node_modules/@os-eco/burrow-cli/src/runtime/registry.ts comment is aspirational). (2) burrow's runSandboxed needs CAP_SYS_ADMIN to mount /proc in a fresh userns; ordinary dev/CI containers without the bwrap-friendly compose flags fail with 'Operation not permitted'. The wrapper at scripts/acceptance/lib/burrow-with-stub.ts imports Client.open() and runServeCommand from @os-eco/burrow-cli, programmatically registers the stub-shell AgentConfig via loadAgentConfig + client.agents.register, and passes a no-bwrap SpawnFn (direct Bun.spawn against the workspace dir) through dispatcherOptions.spawn. inproc.ts's spawnBurrow then launches 'bun run burrow-with-stub.ts' instead of 'burrow serve'. Production warren still runs 'burrow serve' via the supervisor — the wrapper is acceptance-only.","id":"mx-157b2b"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-10T17:45:01.131Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-392b","commit":"15314eb163cf5e8e0fc196ae361d4ace838a956c"},"dir_anchors":["scripts/acceptance/scenarios"],"content":"Acceptance container mode (scripts/acceptance/lib/compose.ts) does NOT bind-mount the host canopy/sample fixtures into the container — the production deploy is fixture-free, so the harness mirrors that shape. Scenarios that need fixtures or that drive process control (kill/restart) declare modes:['in-proc']; container mode runs only scenarios 01 (boot/healthz/readyz) and 13 (container smoke). Override yaml in tmp inlines WARREN_API_TOKEN, WARREN_BURROW_NO_AUTH=1, blank CANOPY_REPO_URL; never reads .env. Each run uses a unique compose project name (warren-acceptance-<random>) so parallel runs don't collide, and a random ephemeral host port mapped to :8080. Boot timeout is 120s (first run builds the image); teardown is 'docker compose down -v --timeout 5'.","id":"mx-96d833"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-10T17:45:19.911Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-392b","commit":"15314eb163cf5e8e0fc196ae361d4ace838a956c"},"dir_anchors":["scripts/acceptance/scenarios"],"content":"package.json exposes 'acceptance' (in-proc default) and 'acceptance:container' (compose-based). ACCEPTANCE.md at repo root is the operator runbook for V1 — covers the trinity (bun test/lint/typecheck), in-proc + container modes, and the three manual gates that the automated harness deliberately doesn't try to cover (--real claude-code run, fly deploy, UI smoke). Manual gates exist because token cost / cloud time / visual inspection can't be cheaply automated; SPEC §11.E–§11.G post-mortems are the canonical list of failure shapes the manual gates catch (warren-67cc, warren-a69a, warren-1eaa, warren-1a09, branchPushed-requires-both-reap-and-sandbox-git).","id":"mx-b79182"}
{"type":"decision","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-10T19:28:40.999Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-4117","commit":"054819c8d43c4e734fe46d5a533d7d8c9c89006e"},"title":"warren-config formats: triggers.yaml + defaults.json (per pl-5d74 step 1)","rationale":"ROADMAP R-02 locks YAML for triggers (cron expressions read better than TOML/JSON, arrays-of-objects are clean) and the plan keeps defaults as JSON for symmetry with the rest of os-eco's UI/API JSON surface and to avoid forcing a YAML round-trip on the simpler defaults file. Note: ROADMAP R-02 originally proposed defaults.yaml; pl-5d74 deviates to defaults.json — captured here so future readers see one source of truth before the ROADMAP edit lands in step 8 (warren-8107).","id":"mx-2cefdd"}
{"type":"decision","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-10T19:28:48.896Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-4117","commit":"054819c8d43c4e734fe46d5a533d7d8c9c89006e"},"title":"YAML parser: js-yaml ^4.1.1 (matches mulch + overstory)","rationale":"pl-5d74 risk #2 calls for using the same YAML lib as siblings to avoid ecosystem drift. mulch (^4.1.1 in deps + ^4.0.9 @types/js-yaml in devDeps) and overstory (@types/js-yaml ^4.0.9 in devDeps) both standardize on js-yaml; seeds/canopy/sapling/greenhouse/burrow have no YAML dep. Picked js-yaml@^4.1.1 + @types/js-yaml@^4.0.9 to mirror mulch's pin exactly. Considered the 'yaml' package — equally maintained but would introduce a second YAML lib into the os-eco install graph.","id":"mx-8b6896"}
{"type":"decision","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-10T23:11:45.600Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-a006","commit":"5ea2580caa0a183a4d8ce2578e277fa8961847cc"},"relates_to":["mx-40fe51"],"title":"Cron lib: croner ^10.0.1 for R-06 scheduler","rationale":"pl-2f15 step 1 picks the cron parser for the R-06 scheduler. Plan approach evaluated four alternatives and selected croner because: (1) small (~30 KB), no native deps, no postinstall scripts — fits warren's tiny-dep posture; (2) tz-aware with explicit DST handling, which a homegrown 5-token parser would skip and later regret (plan risk #2); (3) actively maintained, MIT-licensed, single file; (4) supports both 5-token (Vixie) and 6-token (seconds) grammars, which lets warren-config keep its loose 'cron expression validation' (mx-40fe51) and defer strict parsing to fire time. Bring-our-own parser was rejected — cron grammar corner cases (step values, ranges, DOW vs DOM, 6-token seconds) would either be wrong or grow into croner anyway.","id":"mx-b64542"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-10T23:15:51.738Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-9d8d","commit":"164be93391b8411054d9d388d489fd3bbe5f96f5"},"content":"Adding a drizzle migration: edit schema.ts → bun run db:generate emits src/db/migrations/NNNN_<random-codename>.sql + meta/NNNN_snapshot.json + appends to _journal.json. Then (1) rename the SQL to a descriptive NNNN_<verb_noun>.sql, (2) update the matching 'tag' in meta/_journal.json so the migrator can find it, (3) run 'bunx biome format --write' on the new snapshot + journal — drizzle-kit emits 2-space indent but biome.json enforces tabs.","id":"mx-3f03bd"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-11T00:11:47.031Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-e992","commit":"92fa70dd0f2abe086d1f40624355fdffc53d2d6a"},"relates_to":["mx-5339d5"],"content":"When R-06 (cron scheduler) ships new trigger kinds or new TriggerSchema fields, update three places in lockstep: ROADMAP R-06 entry, SPEC §11.I (and §11.H if the warren-config schema changes), and acceptance scenario 15 (scripts/acceptance/scenarios/15-triggers-roundtrip.ts). New TriggerSchema fields must stay additive (all-optional) so existing triggers.yaml files keep parsing — warren-config (R-02) and the dispatcher (R-06) co-own the schema. Sibling lockstep convention to mx-5339d5 (R-02).","id":"mx-fae553"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-12T19:12:14.590Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-e576","commit":"2393fe995907a23623d387977b7a8d262fd987ca"},"content":"User-facing positioning (README, SPEC §1/§2, package.json description, CLAUDE.md opener, Dockerfile/fly.toml comments) leads with what warren *does* — spawn sandboxed agents at GitHub repos, watch live, steer, get a branch — NOT with the four-tool composition. The os-eco data-plane tools (canopy/mulch/seeds/sapling) are 'opt-in built-in features' that ship in every image but are not required for a fresh install: claude-code is inline, canopy activates on CANOPY_REPO_URL, mulch/seeds activate on per-project .mulch/.seeds/ directories, sapling is just another inline agent. When updating docs that name-drop the four tools as prerequisites, demote them to a 'Power features' section (warren-e576).","id":"mx-345d52"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-12T19:41:12.779Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-f8c0","commit":"7fae0df35eb9faf8d8f099e1d115f4e2703e48b9"},"content":".env.example documents multi-provider keys (OPENAI_API_KEY, GEMINI_API_KEY, GOOGLE_API_KEY, PI_API_KEY, GROQ_API_KEY, MISTRAL_API_KEY, DEEPSEEK_API_KEY) commented out by default (warren-f8c0). The supervisor inherits container env into both warren and burrow children via Bun.spawn without an explicit env: {} — no docker-compose.yml change needed. Burrow's piRuntime.envPassthrough is what actually forwards the keys into the sandbox; warren just makes sure they reach the burrow process.","id":"mx-9c878d"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-13T15:05:35.927Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-a7dc","commit":"7fae0df35eb9faf8d8f099e1d115f4e2703e48b9"},"dir_anchors":["src/runs"],"content":"Drizzle-generated migrations land with a random name (e.g. 0006_dusty_jimmy_woo.sql). Rename to the project convention (0006_add_run_cost_columns.sql) and update the matching tag in src/db/migrations/meta/_journal.json in the same change — drizzle reads the tag from the journal, not the filename. The companion meta/NNNN_snapshot.json stays as-is (keyed by idx, not name).","id":"mx-88ab54"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-13T15:59:53.352Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-0e06","commit":"1eefa67db1e54b617acec8ea1206485c886a959a"},"content":"'bun run lint' (biome check --error-on-warnings .) descends into .claude/worktrees/<branch>/ and fails with 'Found a nested root configuration' when agent worktrees exist locally — each worktree has its own biome.json. Workaround: run 'bunx biome check --error-on-warnings src/ scripts/ drizzle.config.ts' to scan explicit paths and bypass the nested-root detection. Pre-existing local-environment condition; biome.json on main is unchanged.","id":"mx-fc127e"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-13T16:05:01.634Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-0e06","commit":"7fd605078e76072b59a175206e5b21d135bbba53"},"content":"Bumping @os-eco/burrow-cli to pick up a new built-in runtime (e.g. piRuntime in 0.2.8) is a pin-only change in three lockstep locations (package.json + bun.lock + Dockerfile; per CLAUDE.md 'Relationship to burrow'). No warren source changes needed — burrow's BUILT_IN_RUNTIMES is loaded by the supervisor's burrow serve. The acceptance harness (scripts/acceptance/lib/burrow-with-stub.ts) keeps its declarative stub registration for the new agent because the agent binary (e.g. pi) isn't installed in CI/dev; production warren talks to burrow's real runtime. Quality gates after bump: bun install → bun test + tsc + biome.","id":"mx-ca1365"}
{"type":"failure","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-13T19:09:57.660Z","evidence":{"commit":"6ea10b1"},"description":"Bun-based docker images (oven/bun:1.2) provide a node-compat shim at /usr/local/bun-node-fallback-bin/node, but that directory is NOT on the PATH burrow exposes inside bwrap (only /usr/local/bin is bind-mounted). CLIs with #!/usr/bin/env node shebangs (like @earendil-works/pi-coding-agent) fail immediately inside the sandbox with 'env: node: No such file or directory'.","resolution":"Add a Dockerfile symlink before WORKDIR: ln -s /usr/local/bun-node-fallback-bin/node /usr/local/bin/node. Confirmed working for pi v0.74.0; bun's shim handles its node-script semantics fine. Same approach generalizes to any node-shebanged CLI installed via 'bun install -g'.","id":"mx-27f385"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-14T00:10:28.671Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-b894","commit":"250f23ad709fac892a885f50f28c471f9d373e2f"},"relates_to":["mx-3aac69"],"content":"Warren version bump for the R-07 disk-seam closure landed as 0.2.0 (warren plan pl-a31c, parent warren-0a83) — the minor bump signals that warren↔burrow is now HTTP-only on every code path except reap's mulch_merge + branch_push. package.json + src/index.ts must move in lockstep (release.yml grep-checks); CHANGELOG.md 0.2.0 entry references burrow plan bur-pl-2467 as the burrow-side R-07 origin.","id":"mx-5cb52a"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-14T00:43:22.029Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-9993","commit":"6c6d88b13407e4ba5c1809eecf204d00ae48628c"},"dir_anchors":["src/runs","src/server"],"content":"WARREN_RUN_BRANCH_PREFIX (warren-9993) env loader lives in src/runs/branch.ts loadRunBranchPrefixFromEnv — same lenient shape as loadAutoOpenPrConfigFromEnv (src/runs/pr.ts): unset/whitespace/invalid → undefined, never throws. Wired in three places: src/server/main.ts bootServer reads once and threads via ServerDeps.runBranchPrefixDefault and BootSchedulerInput.runBranchPrefixDefault; src/cli/commands/run.ts defaults deps.runBranchPrefixDefault to a fresh loadRunBranchPrefixFromEnv() call (passing null forces the built-in 'burrow' for tests). Documented in .env.example below the WARREN_AUTO_OPEN_PR block.","id":"mx-a7f7db"}
{"type":"reference","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-14T00:59:43.313Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-17a4","commit":"225faad7ee823891469b983b21e938f12297430a"},"name":"acceptance pi declarative outputFormat gap","description":"The acceptance harness registers pi as a declarative agent (scripts/acceptance/lib/burrow-with-stub.ts PI_AGENT_CONFIG with outputFormat:'raw-text'). Burrow's declarative agent only supports raw-text / stream-json / jsonl-claude (burrow src/runtime/declarative.ts:130-134) — there is no jsonl-pi outputFormat. So even after warren-17a4's in-stream cost extraction landed, scenario 16 (16-pi-parity-smoke.ts) still can't assert non-null cost_usd / tokens_* — burrow wraps each pi-shaped JSONL line as {kind:'text', stream:'stdout'} and the bridge's turn_end predicate never matches. Three unblock paths: (1) add jsonl-pi as a declarative outputFormat upstream, (2) install pi binary in CI + switch harness to real piRuntime, (3) register a built-in-style wrapper using parsePiEvents directly.","files":[".seeds/issues.jsonl","src/runs/stream.test.ts","src/runs/stream.ts"],"id":"mx-f1e545"}
