{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-14T05:28:48.535Z","evidence":{"commit":"738ecf14eb772f24c0601f0e0c72bb4502587444"},"content":"warren's named volume 'warren_data' (declared in docker-compose.yml) lands on the host as 'warren_warren_data' because docker compose prefixes named volumes with the project name. When running one-shot containers against the data volume (sqlite surgery, manual db inspection), mount warren_warren_data. Verify with 'docker inspect warren --format {{json .Mounts}}' first. Mounting the unprefixed name silently creates a fresh empty volume — symptom is /data appearing empty when warren clearly populated it.","id":"mx-88447c"}
{"type":"failure","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-14T06:00:00.069Z","evidence":{"commit":"14ac62c36c0d9ae0b6bf122ecefed0623e528f60"},"description":"node_modules/@os-eco/burrow-cli stale per-file symlinks: warren's install of @os-eco/burrow-cli pinned at ^0.3.0 was a local-link install (each src file symlinked to ../burrow/src/...). When burrow added new files post-install (e.g. src/runtime/parsers/pi.ts after warren-17a4 / burrow-d949 landed), the symlinks didn't auto-populate. Symptom: tsc --noEmit fails with 'Cannot find module @os-eco/burrow-cli/src/runtime/parsers/pi.ts or its corresponding type declarations' even though the source file exists in the linked burrow checkout; bun test also fails to resolve the import.","resolution":"rm -rf node_modules/@os-eco/burrow-cli && bun install — force-refreshes the install with the current registry tarball (which includes pi.ts because 459f7a2 predates burrow's 0.3.0 release commit 0639971). A plain 'bun install' is a no-op when the lockfile is satisfied; the rm is required to defeat the cache.","id":"mx-4bc9a7"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-14T16:24:53.851Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-bca1","commit":"35179a317e10178917555c7bba78dd2e23ab67e9"},"relates_to":["mx-5339d5"],"content":"When R-13 (Postgres backend) ships schema or env-contract changes, update docs in lockstep across SEVEN surfaces: SPEC.md §3.2 (V1 non-goals list), §6 (Tech Stack DB row + 'No Postgres' line), §10.1/§10.2 (Deploy), §11.J (org-readiness direction); README.md (V1 today + 'Where this is going' list + Fly.io deploy snippet); ROADMAP.md (R-13 entry + Wave-2 sequencing list); .env.example (storage section); fly.toml (operator-workflow comment); docker-compose.yml (volume comment). Pattern mirrors mx-5339d5 (R-02) and mx-fae553 (R-06). The shipped doc edit landed via seed warren-bca1 (pl-f17e step 9, 2026-05-14).","id":"mx-353d90"}
{"type":"failure","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-14T21:57:25.106Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-2680","commit":"1369d6beb75da0083ea85e5b5fe308926be0fce7"},"description":"R-13 Postgres support shipped half-complete in v0.3.2. CHANGELOG announced 'warren now supports Postgres as an opt-in backend via WARREN_DB_URL=postgres://...' but the repo layer (src/db/repos/*.ts) uses sqlite-only drizzle APIs internally: .get(), .run(), .all(), sync db.transaction(). Outer wiring (URL parsing, openDatabase, migrations, schema parity) is real and works; the moment any repo method runs against pg, it crashes. Two dialect guards (src/server/main.ts:createReposForDialect, src/cli/context.ts:withCliDb) backstop with a fail-fast pointing at pl-f17e step 7 marker. Lesson: when a feature ships via multi-step plan, the CHANGELOG should describe what's actually wired end-to-end, not what the plan title claims.","resolution":"Tracked under plan pl-f1be (warren-2680). Approach: add dialect-polymorphic drizzle adapter (pickOne/pickAll/runWrite/runInTransaction), migrate all 7 repos to it smallest-first, widen createRepos to AnyWarrenDb, delete guards, add CI postgres matrix, validate via scenario 19, then retry dogfood deploy. Until shipped, stick with sqlite-on-volume and warn against WARREN_DB_URL=postgres:// in operator docs.","id":"mx-d1caf7"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-14T21:57:40.500Z","evidence":{"commit":"1369d6beb75da0083ea85e5b5fe308926be0fce7"},"content":"When connecting node-postgres to Supabase, append 'uselibpqcompat=true&sslmode=require' to the connection string. Without it, pg-connection-string v2 treats sslmode=require as verify-full, and Node's default trust store rejects Supabase's pooler cert chain with SELF_SIGNED_CERT_IN_CHAIN. The uselibpqcompat flag is the documented escape hatch (warning emitted by deprecatedSslModeWarning at pg-connection-string/index.js:216). Companion: when sourcing .env files that contain pg URLs with '&' in the query string, single-quote the value so 'set -a; source <file>' doesn't fork on the ampersand. fly secrets import strips surrounding quotes per dotenv conventions, so the URL Fly stores is clean. Both gotchas discovered 2026-05-14 during dogfood deploy — re-validate when warren-2680 ships.","id":"mx-b1e338"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-14T22:40:04.708Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-627b","commit":"36daf57e6d682e9d36591a11536d5135643b961e"},"content":".github/workflows/ci.yml runs two parallel jobs: 'ci' (lint + typecheck + sqlite 'bun test') and 'ci-postgres' (a second 'bun test' against a postgres:16 services container with job-level env WARREN_TEST_DIALECT=postgres + WARREN_TEST_PG_URL=postgres://warren:warren@127.0.0.1:5432/warren_test). The pg job mirrors the sqlite job's test step only — lint + typecheck are dialect-independent and live in 'ci' alone. Repo test suites (src/db/repos/*.test.ts) iterate both dialects via 'if (isPostgresTestEnabled()) suite(\"postgres\")', so 'bun test' under the pg env naturally adds the pg suites on top of the sqlite ones. When adding a new repo or schema, mirror the same suite() pattern so it picks up pg coverage in CI for free.","id":"mx-c47ad1"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-14T22:47:19.816Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-670f","commit":"84e2ae1f33397a9f2a77806ee46a72837acdc4fe"},"relates_to":["mx-d1caf7"],"content":"When a CHANGELOG entry overstates a release (e.g. R-13 in v0.3.2 announcing Postgres support that crash-looped on first repo call), amend the original release section with a brief blockquote 'Correction (date):' callout that points at the follow-up plan, then add the actual completion as a new [Unreleased] entry. The blockquote preserves the audit trail without rewriting history; the [Unreleased] entry is where the real fix is recorded.","id":"mx-eae53c"}
{"type":"failure","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-14T22:55:26.411Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-f451","commit":"a388666900ee4d9e0b585c7e7ad5281f3483f6fe"},"relates_to":["mx-345d52"],"description":"Fly secrets carried over from local docker-compose can poison the Fly deploy. Specifically: CANOPY_REPO_URL=file:///canopy-source (the bind-mount path docker-compose injects via the CANOPY_SOURCE_DIR volume) was set on the warren-deployed Fly app from an earlier session and surfaced after the 2026-05-14 dogfood deploy as 'canopy_unavailable: /canopy-source does not appear to be a git repository' on POST /agents/refresh and ok:false on /readyz canopy_clone + canopy_clean. The file:/// scheme only resolves inside the compose bind-mount; Fly Machines have no /canopy-source path. Built-in agents (claude-code, sapling, pi) ship inline and do not need canopy, so canopy is opt-in per SPEC §1. README's fly.toml comment block correctly has CANOPY_REPO_URL commented out as the default.","resolution":"Run 'fly secrets unset CANOPY_REPO_URL -a <app>' on any Fly deploy that doesn't have a real https git URL for a canopy library. The unset bounces the machine; /readyz then reports 'no canopy library configured (using built-in agents only)' with ok:true. Audit fly secrets list after first deploy and remove any local-dev-only values.","id":"mx-8ab5e7"}
{"type":"pattern","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-14T22:55:38.854Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-f451","commit":"a388666900ee4d9e0b585c7e7ad5281f3483f6fe"},"relates_to":["mx-b1e338"],"name":"fly-supabase-dogfood-end-to-end-shape","description":"Successful warren Fly+Supabase dogfood, 2026-05-14, after pl-f1be (R-13 completion). Observable shape: (1) fly secrets set WARREN_DB_URL='postgresql://postgres:<pw>@db.<ref>.supabase.co:5432/postgres?sslmode=require&uselibpqcompat=true' (single-quote the value when sourcing .env so '&' doesn't fork the shell; fly strips the quotes per dotenv conventions). (2) fly deploy + fly machine start. (3) GET /healthz returns 200. (4) GET /readyz with Bearer WARREN_API_TOKEN returns ok:true across all 11 checks: db_reachable.dialect=postgres, burrow_reachable, agents, canopy_clone (no canopy library configured), bwrap=bubblewrap 0.8.0, warren_config (no projects), preview_* gated on dialect=sqlite. (5) POST /projects gitUrl=<repo> → 201 with prj_<id>. (6) POST /runs agent=claude-code project=<id> prompt='print foo and exit' → 200 with run_<id>, state:queued. (7) Within ~4s, run transitions queued→running→succeeded; reap.completed event has branchPushed:true, commitsAhead:0 (no-op pushes are valid 'success' shape — the reap.empty_push warning event surfaces the work-loss case operators must watch for, per warren-f3bb / SPEC §11.G). pg paths exercised: ProjectsRepo INSERT/SELECT, RunsRepo INSERT/UPDATE/SELECT, EventsRepo INSERT (411 events), AgentsRepo SELECT, BurrowsRepo INSERT/SELECT. If POST /projects returns 'target path already exists' the previous (crashed) deploy stranded /data/projects/<owner>/<repo>; 'fly ssh console -C \"rm -rf <path>\"' clears it.","files":[".mulch/expertise/build.jsonl",".seeds/issues.jsonl",".seeds/plans.jsonl","CHANGELOG.md"],"id":"mx-a629b6"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-15T01:22:42.777Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-810f","commit":"280628edb2636dbb1eb019f19bd69da18d2d4690"},"relates_to":["mx-27f385"],"content":"Dockerfile bakes pnpm@11.1.2 + npm@11.14.1 alongside the other JS CLIs via 'bun install -g' so per-run preview sidecars (R-19 / SPEC §11.L) can boot 'pnpm dev' / 'npm run dev' for projects that don't use bun (warren-810f). Both rely on the existing /usr/local/bin/node bun-shim symlink installed for pi compat (mx-27f385). When bumping these, treat it the same as the other CLI pins — version is a deliberate image-rebuild decision.","id":"mx-8e9c40"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-15T01:57:15.615Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-ac54","commit":"1493d957340e989ce415cda0660423cad3d61bc9"},"content":"CI auto-deploy to Fly is wired as a deploy job in .github/workflows/release.yml that 'needs: release' and gates on needs.release.outputs.release == 'true', so no-op pushes to main don't redeploy. The release job exposes 'release' and 'version' via outputs:. Concurrency group 'fly-deploy-warren-deployed' serializes overlapping releases without cancelling. Token is provisioned via 'fly tokens create deploy -a warren-deployed --name github-actions --expiry 8760h | gh secret set FLY_API_TOKEN -R jayminwest/warren' — scoped to a single app, cannot list secrets or ssh. Uses superfly/flyctl-actions/setup-flyctl@master + 'flyctl deploy --remote-only --app warren-deployed'. Reference shape documented in README's 'Continuous deployment from GitHub Actions' section as the recipe operators can copy for their own warren installs.","id":"mx-991233"}
{"type":"pattern","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-15T01:57:21.299Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-ac54","commit":"1493d957340e989ce415cda0660423cad3d61bc9"},"name":"self-validating-ci-release","description":"When the CI release flow is the unit under test (e.g. adding a new deploy job), bundle the workflow change + a real code change into one version bump. The release proves out both: workflow correctness AND that the underlying code change ships to production. v0.3.5 shipped the deploy job AND the pg-init FK qualifier fix (a38c687) — pushing main → release.yml ran → tag created → deploy job fired → Fly machine rolled from v12→v13 → /readyz green with v0.3.4's preview probes (0/1001 ports, 0/20 live previews) now actually running in prod. A pure no-op version burn would have proved the workflow but had nothing to release; a workflow-only commit can't prove the deploy job fires without bumping the version. The bundle is the dogfood.","files":[".mulch/expertise/build.jsonl",".seeds/issues.jsonl","README.md"],"id":"mx-a35851"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-15T02:28:18.742Z","evidence":{"commit":"23f69d112935edd0eeee60c9b61a1d601b4651f6"},"content":"Biome lint/style/noNonNullAssertion is enforced in test files too. Patterns like 'expect(dec.decode(out!))' where out is T|null fail the lint gate even after expect(out).not.toBeNull(). Refactor with a helper that narrows + throws on null (e.g. function inject(html): string { const out = injectBaseHref(...); if (out === null) throw new Error('expected ...'); return dec.decode(out); }) so subsequent uses are typed-non-null.","id":"mx-bc8fcc"}
{"type":"convention","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-15T02:28:20.529Z","evidence":{"commit":"23f69d112935edd0eeee60c9b61a1d601b4651f6"},"content":"Passing Uint8Array directly to 'new Response(body, init)' fails tsc strict-mode type-check on Bun: TS reports 'Uint8Array<ArrayBufferLike> is not assignable to BodyInit' even though the runtime accepts it. The mismatch is the parameterized Uint8Array<ArrayBufferLike> in current Bun lib types vs BodyInit's BufferSource union. Cast via 'startBytes as unknown as BodyInit' at the new Response call site. Same Uint8Array works as ReadableStreamController enqueue arg without a cast.","id":"mx-5be75e"}
{"type":"failure","classification":"tactical","recorded_at":"2026-05-15T03:49:39.302Z","evidence":{"seeds":"warren-a82b","gh":"jayminwest/jayminwest.com/pull/13","commit":"97b4cb64489150a45dd00853eb4eedba73af1c24"},"tags":["preview","dockerfile","bun","runtime","architectural"],"relates_to":["mx-87d34c"],"description":"Per-run preview sidecar runs Node-targeted projects (next/vite/remix) on Bun, not real Node. Dockerfile:89 symlinks /usr/local/bin/node → /usr/local/bun-node-fallback-bin/node for pi shebang compat (warren-810f). warren-810f baked pnpm+npm for non-bun preview projects but reused the same shim, so 'pnpm dev' → next bin → exec node → loads under Bun. Bun has different built-in module coverage than Node; any dep requiring node:sqlite (and likely other modern node: built-ins) crashes immediately. Verified 2026-05-15 on warren-deployed run_jegavdzfbrpc against Next.js 14.2.24: previewFailureMessage was 'No such built-in module: node:sqlite / Bun v1.2.23'. Acceptance scenario 20-preview*.ts uses python3 -m http.server (mx-87d34c), so no Node runtime ever crosses the symlink — gap invisible in CI.","resolution":"Install real Node alongside Bun in Dockerfile apt-get layer; relocate the bun-shim symlink off PATH and patch pi's shebang to #!/usr/bin/env bun (or symlink it where only pi resolves). Bumping oven/bun:1.2 to a newer tag (Bun 1.2.42+ adds node:sqlite) is whack-a-mole — fixes this error, leaves the architectural mismatch for the next missing built-in. Add a Node-runtime acceptance scenario (next or vite dev) so the gap can't reopen.","id":"mx-c8127d"}

